[2] Samoa: vaccination campaign
Date: Wed 4 Dec 2019
Source: Government of Samoa [abridged, edited]
https://www.facebook.com/samoagovt/photos/measles-vaccination-campaign-as-of-04122019-as-of-2-december-2019-the-government/2794936057204065/


Measles vaccination campaign
----------------------------
As of 2 Dec 2019, the Government of Samoa is providing free vaccination for all Samoan's aged 6 months to 60 years, in an effort to stop the current measles outbreak.

This booster dose will provide a person with 95% lifelong protection against measles.

Vaccination provides the safest and best protection against measles.

Key Information for the public:
1. Priority group for vaccination -- 6 months to 4 years: those who most need to be vaccinated are infants and children aged 6 months to 4 years. Our youngest Samoan's are the most at risk of suffering serious complications from measles, including death, and remain the least vaccinated age group. Parents and families must vaccinate their young children to protect them against measles.

2. People outside of the priority group (5 years-60 years): individuals in the other age groups are at a reduced risk of suffering severe measles, however, they are recommended to be vaccinated if they haven't previously received a measles vaccine or had measles.

3. Individuals who should not be vaccinated are individuals who
- have received a measles vaccine (MR or MMR [measles, mumps, rubella]) in the past 28 days;
- are a pregnant woman;
- have had an allergic reaction to a previous dose of a measles vaccine;
- are severely immunocompromised (such as people with HIV or leukemia, and those receiving chemotherapy or large doses of corticosteroids);
- have been diagnosed as having measles during the current outbreak. A person who gets measles is given lifelong protection against the virus.

4. Individuals who have received a booster dose of measles vaccine since [1 Oct 2019] should not receive another dose of measles vaccine.

Individuals and parents should discuss with the vaccination team if they have any concerns or questions regarding vaccination.

