[6] Taiwan ex Thailand
Date: Wed 4 Dec 2019
Source: Taipei Times [abridged, edited]
http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2019/12/04/2003726935


The Centers for Disease Control (CDC) yesterday [3 Dec 2019] reported a new measles case in northern Taiwan.

The new confirmed measles case is a woman in her 30s living in New Taipei City who has taken public buses and visited clinics and hospitals during the communicability period, CDC Epidemic Intelligence Center Director Liu Ting-ping said.

The agency's preliminary estimate is that about 480 people had direct contact with the woman and would be monitored for symptoms until [Fri [13 Dec 2019], she said.

The woman visited Thailand from [7 to 16 Nov 2019]; she began experiencing the symptoms of fever, throat pain, rashes, and shortness of breath on [21 Nov 2019] and first sought treatment at a clinic on [22 Nov 2019], CDC physician Huang Wan-ting said.

She was diagnosed with a cold on her 1st and 2nd visits to a clinic for treatment, Huang said, adding that she on Monday last week [25 Nov 2019] sought treatment at a hospital, where doctors initially suspected that she had a urinary tract infection.

However, test results on [30 Nov 2019] confirmed that the woman had contracted measles, Huang said, adding that she remained hospitalized.

[see source URL above for locations of possible exposure.]

As the woman has asthma, the shortness of breath she experienced along with the onset of other symptoms, which are common indicators of measles infection, might have led doctors to misdiagnose her because the disease has not been spreading in Taiwan, CDC Deputy Director-General Philip Lo said.

Measles is at its peak in Viet Nam, Indonesia, Thailand, and other Southeast Asian countries, so people who plan to visit the region should consult a doctor about receiving a vaccination in advance and inform doctors about their travel if they develop a fever or rashes after returning to Taiwan, he said.

Separately, 861 hospital visits for chickenpox were reported last week [week of 25 Nov 2019], more than the previous 2 weeks, and 16 cluster cases have been reported in the past 4 weeks, mostly on school campuses, Liu said.

[Byline: Lee I-chia]

